name: Use centralized error handling
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: error
if: Manual error state management with useState or direct error handling
then: Use useErrorHandler hook and ErrorDisplay component for consistent error handling
why: Centralized error handling provides consistent user experience, proper error categorization, and retry mechanisms.
globs: ["frontend/src/components/**/*.tsx", "frontend/src/hooks/**/*.ts"]

---
name: Categorize errors properly
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Generic error handling without proper categorization
then: Use ErrorType enum (NETWORK, VALIDATION, AUTHENTICATION, etc.) and ErrorSeverity levels
why: Proper error categorization enables better user feedback and debugging.
globs: ["frontend/src/**/*.ts", "frontend/src/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Implement retry mechanisms
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Error handling without retry capabilities for transient errors
then: Use useErrorHandler's retry mechanism with exponential backoff
why: Retry mechanisms improve user experience for transient network or server errors.
globs: ["frontend/src/components/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Use ErrorDisplay component
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: error
if: Manual Alert components or custom error UI
then: Use ErrorDisplay component with proper error info and actions
why: ErrorDisplay provides consistent error UI with proper styling, icons, and actions.
globs: ["frontend/src/components/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Handle API errors consistently
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: error
if: API calls without proper error handling or categorization
then: Use centralized API client with error categorization and proper HTTP status mapping
why: Consistent API error handling improves debugging and user experience.
globs: ["frontend/src/services/**/*.ts", "frontend/src/hooks/**/*.ts"]

---
name: Provide user-friendly error messages
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Technical error messages shown to users
then: Use getUserFriendlyMessage function to translate technical errors to user-friendly messages
why: User-friendly error messages improve user experience and reduce support requests.
globs: ["frontend/src/**/*.ts", "frontend/src/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Clear errors on new actions
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Not clearing errors when starting new operations
then: Call clearError() at the start of async operations
why: Clearing errors prevents stale error messages from confusing users.
globs: ["frontend/src/components/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Handle loading states with errors
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Loading states that don't account for error conditions
then: Ensure loading states are properly managed with error handling
why: Proper loading state management prevents UI inconsistencies during error scenarios.
globs: ["frontend/src/components/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Log errors for debugging
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: info
if: Errors without proper logging
then: Use console.error or proper logging service for error tracking
why: Error logging helps with debugging and monitoring application health.
globs: ["frontend/src/**/*.ts", "frontend/src/**/*.tsx"]

---
name: Test error scenarios
scope: typescript
language: typescript
severity: warning
if: Components without error handling tests
then: Write tests for error scenarios, retry mechanisms, and error display
why: Error handling tests ensure robust error recovery and user experience.
globs: ["frontend/src/**/*.test.tsx", "frontend/src/**/*.spec.tsx"]
description:
globs:
alwaysApply: false
---
